Coursera Bellabeat

Trude

10/1/2021

Introduction

Bellabeat is a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products.Their product offerings range from the Bellabeat app, the Leaf wellness tracker (necklace/bracelet/clip), the wellness watch Time, the Spring water bottle, and a a subscription-based membership program. All their physical product connect to the app to track activity, sleep, and stress, hydration levels, and more, to provide users with insights into their overall daily wellness.

This small but successful company aims to become a larger player in the global smart device market, and use the findings from this analysis to guide their marketing strategy.

Business Task

To gain insights into how consumers are using their smart devices by analyzing smart device usage trends, the company wants to identify new growth opportunities to become a larger player in the global smart device market.

Some questions to consider:

  • What are some trends in smart device usage?
  • How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  • How could these trends help influence the Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Let’s get started…

Installing and loading common packages and libraries

Setting up my environment by loading the following packages: tidyverse, here, skimr, janitor for cleaning the data and for organizing the data dplyr to filter the data, and ggplot2 for visualization.

Loading the CSV files

The data source I used is : FitBit Fitness Tracker Data The datasets in this source were generated by respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03.12.2016-05.12.2016. Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. Variation between output represents the use of different types of Fitbit trackers and individual tracking behaviors/preferences (Möbius, 2016).

A few things to note here are that the data source is from 2016, so not very current. It mentions different types of users but doesn’t specify how different these types of users were. Also, the sample size is very small, and there’s no data on hydration levels.

Let’s do a ROCCC analysis: Reliable: Kaggle gives it a usability ranking of 10. Original: It’s not the original source, it was surveyed via Amazon Mechanical Turk. Current, It was surveyed between 03.12.2016-05.12.2016, so it’s not very current. Comprehensive: It does not seem comprehensive because it might not contain all critical information needed to answer the question or find the solution. Cited The source is cited, This survey has been created by Amazon Mechanical Turk so it Is it part of a credible organization and it has been refreshed recently. Other sources might be needed here.

Further examination of the data source, reveals there are many csv files in the data source. I will be quickly scanning them to determine which are useful and relevant. I notice calories, daily activity, intensities, sleep, weight, steps, and heart rate.

On to creating the following data frames:

  • daily_activity
  • sleep_day
  • weight_log
  • daily_calories

  • daily_steps

The daily activity_table already contains the data for daily_calories, daily_intensities, and daily_steps data. The number of observations in these tables are exactly the same, so I will just focus on the following tables:

  • daily_activity,
  • sleep,
  • weight_log

Here you can see that the participants average 7638 of total steps a day, cover an average of 5.49 miles a day, and on average are sitting down for 991.2 minutes per day or 16.52 hours per day. According to the CDC a good goal is 10.000 steps or 5 miles a day. According to Just Stand Org, “VERY HIGH risk indicates sitting more than 11 hours per day”. So, for health benefits, users should make more steps and cover more distance a day and sit for less amounts of time.

The average weight of the participants was 158lbs, but we don’t know if the participants were male or female, their ages, and in addition to the low sample size, we can’t really derive any information from this number. Just to compare, according to the CDC, the measured average weight for adults aged 20 and over for men is 199.8 pounds and for women is 170.8 pounds.

The average body fat percentage was 23.5 and the average number for BMI was 25.19. According to Medical News Today, a body fat percentage of 23.5 is either fair, poor, or dangerously high depending on the sex and age group, and “A BMI between 25 and 29.9 indicates that a person has overweight”.

A good goal here is to lose weight, lower the body fat percentage and obtaining a lower BMI.

DATA VISUALIZATION

From looking at the statistics I will investigate the following:

  • The relationship between activity, steps, distance and calories
  • The relationship between total steps and sedentary minutes
  • The relationship between minutes asleep vs time in bed
  • The relationship between activity and sleep
  • The relationship between activity and weight

Plotting a few explorations now.

Activity vs. Calories

What is the relationship between the level of activity and the calories burnt? I would expect that the more active you are, the more calories you burn, but let’s find out to be certain:

Let’s calculate the Correlation coefficients for very active minutes vs calories:

## [1] 0.6158383

That’s a moderate positive relationship. This means that the more active the participant was, the more calories they burned.

For sedentary minutes vs calories:

## [1] -0.106973

For sedentary minutes per day and calories burnt per day there is no correlation at all. This means that the amount of time you are non-active has no effect on the amount of calories you burn. For less active users, they need to become more active to start burning more calories.

Total Steps vs Calories

Let’s calculate the correlation coefficient now:

## [1] 0.5915681

This means that there is a moderate positive relationship between total steps taken per day and calories burnt.

Total Distance vs Calories

Let’s calculate the correlation coefficient now:

## [1] 0.6449619

That’s also a moderate positive correlation. The more distance the participants covered, the more calories they burned.

If people can view how active they are, how many steps they are taking, what distance they have covered, and how many calories they burn, they are encouraged to become even more active.

Total Steps vs Sedentary Minutes

What’s the relationship between steps taken in a day and sedentary minutes?

Let’s calculate the Correlation coefficient:

## [1] -0.3274835

The graph shows a downhill line, but the points are very scattered, showing a negative linear relationship is present, but not very strong. This means that there is a very weak negative relationship between total steps per day and sedentary minutes.

Looks like the more steps users made the less non-active they were, and reversely, the more non-active minutes spent the less steps they took. We could position this as a way to encourage people to become more active, by just taking more steps a day.

Minutes Asleep vs Time in Bed

Let’s find out about the relationship between minutes asleep and time in bed. I would expect this to be almost completely linear, let’s find out:

## [1] 0.9304575

Wow, very close to “1”, so there is a strong positive linear relationship, indeed, but with some outliers. This makes sense because time spent in bed is sometimes not entirely spent on sleeping. These trends show that being able to check your time in bed versus the time you actually sleep provides insights in your sleep habits.

Now I am wondering: does sleep have an effect on your activity? Are you more active if you sleep longer? I would like to explore this further.

Activity vs. Sleep

Let’s explore the relationship between activity and sleep now.

We have already merged the two tables together in the previous combined_data_2 dataset, so let’s plot it:

Let’s calculate the correlation coefficient to make sense of this:

## [1] -0.07018517

Looking at the graph and noting from the correlation calculation, there does not appear to be any relation between these two variables! Participants who sleep longer do not take more or fewer steps per day, and reversely, being more active does not mean that you sleep longer. Note, that his doesn’t say anything about the quality of sleep though.

Maybe the focus of the marketing strategy on how you position the product should not be too much/less on the sleep feature.

Surprisingly, the more steps particpants did, the higher the weight gain in pounds. According the the correlation coefficient there’s only a weak linear negative relationship. Keep in mind that only 8 of the 33 users recorded weight so this information is not very reliable. A thought is that the participants did not want to reveal their weight, or maybe it’s just inconvenient.A solution, and also an opportunity, is to this is to offer a smart scale that connects to the Bellabeat app.

Conclusions

There are more observations of participants activity, steps, and distance covered, than observations about sleep hours and weight data, and there are more unique participants for activity than for sleep and weight. This is probably because the activity, steps, distance, and sleep hours data is automatically tracked and weight has to be entered manually. Because only few participants have logged their weight, users should be encouraged to enter their weight to fully benefit from Bellabeat’s product features.

No hydration data was collected, so the participants have not been using a smart hydration bottle, like the Bellabeat’s Spring water bottle. This opens the door for Bellabeat to start actively marketing their Spring bottle as this sets them apart from the competition. I also suggest using the users daily steps data along with the hydration data to adjust (and maybe push) the users daily hydration goal for the day based on their activity level.

Even though there is no relation between sleep hours per day and activity, promoting better sleep habits is likely very important for Bellabeat’s target customers, and therefore the sleep feature should be focused on more as informational or just encouragement to make sure the user gets enough sleep.

For users who want to track their weight, they should be encouraged logging their weight daily. This can be accomplished by piloting a smart scale that connect to the app.

Recommendations:

  • Promote all Bellabeat products by offering bundle deals, discounts, etc.
  • Promote the Spring smart water bottle, as this sets the company apart from the competition.
  • Start offering a smart scale to encourage weight logging, and to bundle with other products. This also sets the company apart from competition.
  • Promote the Bellabeat membership by offering discounts when bundling with other products.
  • Make it easy for all results to be shared with friends to encourage users to become more healthy.
  • Enable alert notifications to encourage users to meet their goals for minutes of activity, calories burned per day, hours of sleep, and weight loss.
  • Encourage users to sit less by alerting them to start moving after a certain period of non-activity.
  • Promote better sleep habits by notifying users of their daily sleep hours.
